the Normans, developing into the Middle English personal name <i>Amery</i>, <i>Emery</i> (from Old French <i>Amauri</i>, <i>Emaurri</i>).","occasionally perhaps also from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Aimery</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Haimeric</i>, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’+ <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’. Compare   Emery  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Amber","meanings":["From the word for the fossilized resin <i>amber</i>, a word derived via Old French and Latin from Arabic <i>ambar</i>. This was first used as a given name at the end of the 19th century. It enjoyed a surge in popularity following the publication of  Kathleen Winsor's  novel Forever Amber in  1944 , and again in the 1990s."]},{"name":"Hembree","meanings":["Altered form of English <b>Hembrey</b>, a variant of   Amery  , with excrescent <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Armey","meanings":["Altered form of English   Amery  ."]},{"name":"Emery","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, derived in the Middle Ages from a personal name introduced to England by the Normans. This was originally composed of the Germanic elements <i>amal</i> ‘bravery, vigour’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power’, but soon assumed a variety of forms such as <i>Amauri</i> and <i>Emauri</i>."]}]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Aymery IV Vicomte de Rochechouart was born in 1070, in France, his father, Aymeric III Vicomte de Rochechouart, was 51 and his mother, Alpaïs de Salignac, was 51. He married Marguerite de Limoges about 1090, in France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He registered for military service in 1099. He died in 1130, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1070–1130":"1070–1130","1047–Female":"1047–Surnud","1050–Male":"1050–Surnud","1052–Male":"1052–Surnud","1058–1105":"1058–1105","1070–Female":"1070–Surnud","1100–1170":"1100–1170","1020–1075":"1020–1075","1020–Female":"1020–Surnud","about 1090":"umbes 1090","1099":"1099","1075":"1075","1130":"1130","1020":"1020","1052":"1052","1050":"1050","from 1073 to 1130":"1073 kuni 1130","1170":"1170","1070":"1070","1105":"1105","1058":"1058","1047":"1047","1100":"1100","after 1045":"pärast 1045","Rochechouart, Limousin, Kingdom of France":"Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Limousin, Prantsusmaa","Rochechouard, Limosin, Kingdom of France":"Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1070–1130":"1070–1130","1047–Female":"1047–Kuollut","1050–Male":"1050–Kuollut","1052–Male":"1052–Kuollut","1058–1105":"1058–1105","1070–Female":"1070–Kuollut","1100–1170":"1100–1170","1020–1075":"1020–1075","1020–Female":"1020–Kuollut","about 1090":"noin 1090","1099":"1099","107